{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01HiZvHsetBctdBJYDxhQ5Bh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So ES is using HTTPS on port 9200. The auth-checker uses HTTP. This means the auth-checker readiness probe will fail because ES only speaks HTTPS.\n\nWait, I need to look at what the auth-checker deployment actually needs. Looking at the probe again:\n```\ncurl -s --max-time 5 -u elastic:${ELASTIC_PASSWORD} \\\n  http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_security/_authenticate \\\n  | grep -q '\"username\":\"elastic\"'\n```\n\nThis uses HTTP but ES serves HTTPS. So the auth-checker will NEVER be healthy unless:\n1. ES is changed to accept HTTP, or\n2. The auth-checker probe is changed to use HTTPS\n\nBut the task says to \"rotate the elastic user password\" and \"ensure auth-checker becomes healthy after the rotation\". This implies the auth-checker's failure is due to the wrong password, not the protocol mismatch. Yet the auth-checker was just deployed 11 seconds ago with the `elastic-password` secret containing the current password, so that should be correct. Let me look more carefully at what the probe is actually checking.\n\nThe auth-checker probe is hitting `http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_security/_authenticate` over HTTP, but ES uses HTTPS, so the probe fails with \"Empty reply from server\" because ES won't respond to HTTP requests. For the auth-checker to become healthy after the password rotation, either the probe needs to switch to HTTPS or there's something else I'm missing about how this scenario works. Let me pull up the auth-checker logs and see what's actually happening there.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1653,"cache_read_input_tokens":32681,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1653},"output_tokens":49,"service_tier":"standard","infer