{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VEhJKC7KRomszaFtV43A9V","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The auth-checker uses HTTP not HTTPS to check ES. But ES only serves HTTPS. So the probe fails because ES closes HTTP connections with an empty reply.\n\nLooking at the auth-checker probe:\n```\ncurl -s --max-time 5 -u elastic:${ELASTIC_PASSWORD} \\\n  http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_security/_authenticate \\\n  | grep -q '\"username\":\"elastic\"'\n```\n\nThis probe will only pass if ES responds to HTTP with a JSON response containing `\"username\":\"elastic\"`. Since ES uses HTTPS, it won't respond on HTTP.\nThe core problem is that the auth-checker will never succeed unless I either disable SSL on ES's HTTP layer or switch the probe to use HTTPS with the `-k` flag. Since I need to make auth-checker healthy, I'm looking at disabling SSL in the ES configuration to allow HTTP connections, which would require a rolling restart of the ES pods. that the auth-checker probe is failing suggests the password rotation itself might be the core issue—if ES was already on HTTPS and the probe was already using HTTP, this would've been broken before. Let me reconsider whether the task expects me to fix both the protocol mismatch and update the password, or if there's something about the current setup I'm missing. Maybe the password management is actually handled through the file realm instead of the native realm—the `file-realm-gen` pod might be generating those user credentials. Let me check what secrets it's creating.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1130,"cache_read_input_tokens":35922,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1130},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool